First we find all numbers that divide evenly into $432$. We have \begin{align*}
432&=2^4\times3^3\\
&\Rightarrow432=\underbrace{2\times2\times2\times2}_\text{4 factors of $2$}\times\underbrace{3\times3\times3}_\text{3 factors of $3$}
\end{align*}By theexistence of prime factorization, we know that there are $(4+1)(3+1)=20$ different factors of $432$, which are \[1,2,3,4,6,8,9,12,16,18,24,27,36,48,54,72,108,144,216,432.\]We may organize them into pyramidal groups of four: \[\begin{align*}&[1,2,4,8],[3,6,12,24],[9,18,36,72],[27,54,108,216]\\&\quad{}+[432]\end{align*}\]The factors in the first four pyramidal groups all divide evenly into $432$, but those of the last group do not. Therefore, $\boxed{431}$ is the only proper divisor of $432$. \end{twise} <answer> 431  </answer>

